    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight> 
          <p>
             <term>Key Takeaway</term>
          </p>
              <p>
             While solving logarithmic equations, it is important to remember the properties of logarithms to help with simplification.
             Kindly ensure that logarithims are of the same base before attempting to solve the equation.
          </p>  
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the logarithmic equation: <m>log₂(x+5) = log₂(2x−1) + 1 </m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
               To solve the equation <m>log₂(x+5) = log₂(2x−1) + 1</m>, use the product rule of logarithms to combine the logarithmic expressions on the right side of the equation. The product rule states that <m>log_b(m) + log_b(n) = log_b(m*n) </m>. Applying this rule gives us:
            </p>
              <p>
                <m>log₂(x+5) = log₂(2x−1) + log₂(2)</m>
              </p>
                <p>
                Now combine the logarithmic expressions on the right side using the product rule again to get:
                </p>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                             <m>log₂(x+5) = log₂((2x−1) * 2)</m>
                             <m>log₂(x+5) = log₂(4x−2)</m>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Rearrange the equation to set the arguments of the logarithms equal to each other as:
                        <m>x + 5 = 4x - 2</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Collect like terms to get:
                        <m>3x = 7</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Solving for x gives us:
                        <m>x = \frac{7}{3}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Finally, you need to check if the solution is valid by substituting it back into the original equation. Ensure that the arguments of the logarithms are positive, as logarithms are only defined for positive numbers.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For log₂(x+5), you have:
                        <m>log₂\left(\frac{7}{3} + 5\right) = log₂\left(\frac{7}{3} + \frac{15}{3}\right) = log₂\left(\frac{22}{3}\right)</m>
                    </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the logarithmic equation: <m>log₃(2x+1) - log₃(x-2) = 1</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To solve the equation <m>log₃(2x+1) - log₃(x-2) = 1</m>, consider using the quotient rule of logarithms, which states that <m>log_b(m) - log_b(n) = log_b(m/n)</m>. Applying this rule gives:
            </p>
              <p>
                <m>log₃\left(\frac{2x+1}{x-2}\right) = 1</m>
              </p>
                <p>
                Now rewrite the equation in exponential form. The equation <m>log_b(a) = c</m> can be rewritten as <m>b^c = a</m>. Applying this to the equation gives us:
                </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>3^1 = \frac{2x+1}{x-2}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Simplifying this gives:
                        <m>3 = \frac{2x+1}{x-2}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Cross-multiplying gives:
                        <m>3(x-2) = 2x + 1</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Expanding the left side gives:
                        <m>3x - 6 = 2x + 1</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Collecting like terms gives:
                        <m>x = 7</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Finally, you need to check if the solution is valid by substituting it back into the original equation. Ensure that the arguments of the logarithms are positive.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For <m>log₃(2x+1)</m>, you have:
                        <m>log₃(2(7)+1) = log₃(15)</m>, which is valid since 15 is positive.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For <m>log₃(x-2)</m>, you have:
                        <m>log₃(7-2) = log₃(5)</m>, which is also valid since 5 is positive.
                    </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the logarithmic equation: <m>log₂(x+5) - log₂(x-3) = 2</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To solve the equation <m>log₂(x+5) - log₂(x-3) = 2</m>, use the quotient rule of logarithms, which states that <m>log_b(m) - log_b(n) = log_b(m/n)</m>. Applying this rule gives:
            </p>
              <p>
                <m>log₂\left(\frac{x+5}{x-3}\right) = 2</m>
              </p>
                <p>
                Now rewrite the equation in exponential form. The equation <m>log_b(a) = c</m> can be rewritten as <m>b^c = a</m>. Applying this to the equation gives us:
                </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>2^2 = \frac{x+5}{x-3}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Simplifying this gives:
                        <m>4 = \frac{x+5}{x-3}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Cross-multiplying gives :
                        <m>4(x-3) = x + 5</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Expanding the left side gives:
                        <m>4x - 12 = x + 5</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Collecting like terms gives:
                        <m>3x = 17</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Solving for x gives us:
                        <m>x = \frac{17}{3}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Finally, check if the solution is valid by substituting it back into the original equation. We need to ensure that the arguments of the logarithms are positive.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For <m>log₂(x+5)</m>, you have:
                        <m>log₂\left(\frac{17}{3} + 5\right) = log₂\left(\frac{17}{3} + \frac{15}{3}\right) = log₂\left(\frac{32}{3}\right)</m>, which is valid since <m>\(\frac{32}{3}\)</m> is positive.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For <m>log₂(x-3)</m>, you have:
                        <m>log₂\left (\frac{17}{3} - 3\right) = log₂\left(\frac{17}{3} - \frac{9}{3}\right) = log₂\left(\frac{8}{3}\right)</m>, which is valid since <m>\(\frac{8}{3}\)</m> is positive.
                    </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

